'''Jakub of Gostynin''' ({{lang-pl|'''Jakub z Gostynina'''}}; ca. 1454 &ndash; 16 February 1506, [[Kraków]]) was a [[Poles|Polish]] [[philosopher]] and [[theologian]] of the late 15th century, and [[Rector (academia)|Rector]] of the [[University of Krakow]] in 1503–4.<ref>[http://www.uj.edu.pl/dispatch.jsp?item=uniwersytet/historia/poczet.jsp&lang=en Past Rectors of the Jagiellonian University of Kraków] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090710133051/http://www.uj.edu.pl/dispatch.jsp?item=uniwersytet%2Fhistoria%2Fpoczet.jsp&lang=en |date=2009-07-10 }} Brief history at JU official website.</ref>
==Life== Jakub of Gostynin was one of the chief adherents of the [[Cologne]]-style [[Thomism]], a philosophical school that upheld the legacy of work and thought of [[Thomas Aquinas]].<ref>[[Władysław Tatarkiewicz]], ''Zarys dziejów filozofii w Polsce'' (A Brief History of Philosophy in Poland), [in the series:] Historia nauki polskiej w monografiach (''History of Polish Learning in Monographs''), [volume] XXXII, Kraków, Polska Akademia Umiejętności ([[Polish Academy of Learning]]), 1948. This monograph draws from pertinent sections in earlier editions of the author's Historia filozofii (History of Philosophy), pp. 6–7.</ref> Jakub's main work, entitled ''"Theoremata seu propositiones Auctoris Causarum"'',<ref>[[Jagiellonian Library]] catalogue number: Kr 1507; wyd. kryt. P. Góra, MHFS 11 (1969), 11–162 (frg. w: Filozofia i myśl społeczna XIII–XV wieku, Wwa 1978,462–476)</ref> was a commentary to ''[[Liber de Causis]]'' attributed to the Greek philosopher [[Aristotle]]. He also wrote a commentary to ''[[Metaphysics (Aristotle)|Metaphysics]]'' by Aristotle entitled: ''"Expositiosuper I–XII libros „Metaphysicae” Aristotelis"'' as well as to his ''[[Physics (Aristotle)|Physics]]''.<ref>Jagiellonian Library catalogue: rps BJ 505 i 2010; Komentarz do „Fizyki”. Wstęp, w: Filozofia i myśl społeczna [...], 445–461</ref> He contributed to commentaries by Paul of Venice (''Paweł z Wenecji'') to ''[[On the Soul]]'' (or "De Anima") by Aristotle and the theological works of [[Jan Versor]]. Jakub of Gostynin is also the author of commentaries on the ''[[Gospel of John]]''. He donated his extensive library of manuscripts of philosophy, theology and language to the University of Krakow.
==See also== *[[History of philosophy in Poland#Scholasticism|History of philosophy in Poland]]
