'''Justin E. H. Smith''' (born July 30, 1972 in [[Reno, Nevada]]) is a professor of history and [[philosophy of science]] at the [[Paris Diderot University|University of Paris 7 - Denis Diderot]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sciences, Philosophie, Histoire – UMR 7219, laboratoire SPHERE - Organigramme du personnel de SPHERE|url = http://www.sphere.univ-paris-diderot.fr/spip.php?rubrique48&lang=fr|website = www.sphere.univ-paris-diderot.fr|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> He has authored several books<ref name=currVitae>{{Cite web|title = Justin E. H. Smith: Curriculum Vitæ|url = http://www.jehsmith.com/philosophy/curriculum-vitae.html|website = www.jehsmith.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> and is also a regular contributor to ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>[http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/author/justin-e-h-smith/?_r=0 The New York Times: Opinionator: Posts published by Justin E. H. Smith]</ref> ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'',<ref>[http://harpers.org/author/justinsmith/ The Joke, By Justin Smith] Harper's Magazine, April 2015</ref> ''[[n+1]]'', ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|title = Why Did the Killers Target the Eagles of Death Metal Concert?|url = http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/foreigners/2015/11/paris_attack_why_the_terrorists_targeted_the_eagles_of_death_metal_concert.html|newspaper = Slate|date = 2015-11-16|access-date = 2015-11-22|issn = 1091-2339|language = en-US|first = Justin E. H.|last = Smith}}</ref> and ''[[Art in America]]''.<ref>[https://www.artinamericamagazine.com/news-features/magazines/cave-art-means/ What Cave Art Means, by Justin E. H. Smith], Art in America, September 1, 2018</ref> Smith is an editor-at-large of ''[[Cabinet Magazine]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cabinetmagazine.org/contributors/smith_justin_e_h.php|title=CABINET // Justin E. H. Smith|work=cabinetmagazine.org}}</ref>
Justin E. H. Smith's primary research Interests include [[Leibniz]], [[early modern philosophy]], [[History of biology|history]] and [[Philosophy of Biology|philosophy of biology]], classical [[Indian Philosophy|Indian philosophy]], and the [[History of Anthropology|history]] and [[Philosophical anthropology|philosophy of anthropology]].
On November 27, 2015, he delivered the annual [[Pierre Bayle]] Lecture to the Pierre Bayle Foundation in Rotterdam, The Netherlands, on "The Gravity of Satire."<ref>{{Cite web|title = Pierre Bayle Stichting — Justin E.H. Smith op 27 november 2015|url = http://www.pierrebayle.nl/lezingen/justin-e-h-smith/|website = www.pierrebayle.nl|accessdate = 2015-12-02}}</ref>
The main-belt asteroid 13585 Justinsmith is named after Justin E. H. Smith.<ref>{{Cite web|title = JPL Small-Body Database Browser|url = http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=13585|website = ssd.jpl.nasa.gov|accessdate = 2015-11-22}}</ref>
Smith is a member of the Esthetical Society for Transcendental and Applied Realization (now incorporating the Society for Esthetic Realisers) (ESTAR(SER)), a research collective dedicated to studying the historicity of the Order of the Third Bird.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.estarser.net/communiques/?page_id=199|title=ESTAR(SER) {{!}} Communiqués from ESTAR (SER)|website=www.estarser.net|access-date=2016-10-26}}</ref>
