'''Karl Fortlage''' ({{IPA-de|ˈfɔɐ̯tˌlaːɡə|lang}}; 12 June 1806 – 8 November 1881) was a German philosopher.
==Biography== Born in [[Osnabrück]], Fortlage taught in [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]] and [[University of Berlin|Berlin]] before becoming professor of philosophy at [[University of Jena|Jena]] in 1846 (1846 associate professor, 1860 honorary professor),<ref>[http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/pnd118684256.html Fortlage, Arnold Rudolf Karl] In: [[Neue Deutsche Biographie]] (NDB). Band 5, Duncker & Humblot, Berlin 1961, {{ISBN|3-428-00186-9}}, S. 304 f.</ref> a post he held until his death. Originally a follower of [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel|Hegel]], he turned to [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte|Fichte]] and the [[psychologist]] [[Friedrich Eduard Beneke]], agreeing with his assertion that psychology is the basis of all philosophy. The fundamental idea of his psychology is [[impulse (psychology)|impulse]], which combines representation (thereby presupposing consciousness) and feeling (i.e. pleasure). [[Reason]] is the highest thing in nature, i.e. it is divine in its nature. God is the absolute [[Ego (religion)|Ego]], and the empirical egos are his instruments. [[File:Jena Johannisfriedhof Fortlage.jpg|right|thumb|Gravesite of Fortlage at Johannisfriedhof in Jena]]
== Principal works == * ''Das musikalische System der Griechen in seiner Urgestalt : aus den Tonleitern des Alypius'', 1847 &ndash; The musical system of the Greeks in its original form * ''Genetische Geschichte der Philosophie seit Kant'', 1852 &ndash; Genetic history of philosophy since [[Immanuel Kant|Kant]]. * ''System der psychologie : als empirischer wissenschaft aus der beobachtung des innern sinnes'', 1855 &ndash; System of psychology; as an empirical science from the observation of the internal sense. * ''Friedrich Rückert und seine Werke'', 1867 &ndash; [[Friedrich Rückert]] and his work. * ''Acht psychologische Vorträge'', 1869 &ndash; Eight psychological lectures. * ''Beiträge zur Psychologie als Wissenschaft aus Speculation und Erfahrung'', 1875 &ndash; Contributions to psychology as a science of speculation and experience.
