{{BLP sources|date=November 2013}} {{nihongo|'''Masachi Osawa'''|大澤 真幸|Ōsawa Masachi|born October 15, 1958 in [[Nagano Prefecture|Nagano]], Japan}} is a Japanese sociologist.
He received his Ph.D in Sociology from the [[University of Tokyo]] in 1990. His Ph.D thesis is {{nihongo|''The Algebra of Actions''|行為の代数学|Koi no Daisugaku}}. His supervisor was [[Munesuke Mita]]. He is one of the most influential sociologists in Japan and a prolific author.<ref>http://osawa-masachi.com/?page_id=250</ref> He has taught at [[Chiba University]] and [[Kyoto University]].
He has contributed to the most influential Japanese postmodern journal {{nihongo|''Critical Space''|批評区間|Hihyōkūkan}}, edited by [[Kojin Karatani]] and [[Akira Asada]]. Outside Japan, he is best known as a social scientist, often mentioned in reference to sociological and philosophical research on [[otaku]] culture and popular Japanese [[Anime|animation series]] such as [[Ghost in the Shell: Stand Alone Complex]].<ref>https://confluence.cornell.edu/display/asian3318/Osawa+Masachi</ref>
