'''''Religion and Nothingness''''' (''{{lang-ja|Shūkyō to wa Nanika}}''; the original title translates literally as "What is Religion?") is a 1961 book by the Japanese philosopher [[Keiji Nishitani]], in which the author discusses [[nihilism]].<ref name="Habito">[[#Hab95|Habito 1995]]. p. 396.</ref> The book was published in English translation in 1982, and received positive reviews, commending Nishitani for his understanding of both western and eastern philosophy. The appearance of the English translation increased interest in Nishitani's ideas among philosophers.

==Reception==
===Overview===
''Religion and Nothingness'' first appeared in English translation in 1982, generating increasing interest in Nishitani's ideas among philosophers, theologians, and religious scholars.<ref name="Habito" />

===Mainstream media===
The book received positive reviews from Donald L. Smith in ''[[Library Journal]]'',<ref name="Smith">[[#Smi83|Smith 1983]]. p. 133.</ref> and J. N. Gray in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]''.<ref name="Gray" /> Smith wrote that Nishitani "presents a subtle philosophical analysis of reality and a lively argument for resolving problems of being in terms of certain metaphysical principles of Zen Buddhism." Smith called the book "profound yet clearly written", and credited Nishitani with "erudite wisdom and understanding of both Eastern and Western philosophical traditions."<ref name="Smith" /> Gray wrote that Nishitani "achieves a remarkable cross-fertilization of the most profound and radical elements in Eastern and Western philosophy and spiritual experience", and that the book "will have the utmost value for all those who see in contemporary Western philosophy the unresolved issue of nihilism, and who are prepared to entertain the supposition that thought emerging from a tradition in which the experience of Nothingness was not threatening, and rather a benediction, may have something to teach us."<ref name="Gray">[[#Gra83|Gray 1983]]. p. 1023.</ref>

===Academic journals===
The book was reviewed by Philip Blosser in ''[[Research in Phenomenology]]'',<ref>[[#Blo84|Blosser 1984]]. pp. 281-288.</ref> the theologian [[Thomas J. J. Altizer]] in ''[[Journal of the American Academy of Religion]]'',<ref>[[#Alt84|Altizer 1984]]. pp. 198-199.</ref> the Buddhist studies scholar [[Bernard Faure]] in ''[[The Journal of Asian Studies]]'',<ref>[[#Fau85|Faure 1985]]. pp. 402-404.</ref> Thomas P. Kasulis in ''[[The Journal of Religion]]'',<ref>[[#Kas85|Kasulis 1985]]. pp. 436-438.</ref> and Richard H. Drummond in ''Journal of Ecumenical Studies''.<ref>[[#Dru85|Drummond 1985]]. pp. 131-135.</ref> James L. Fredericks wrote in ''[[The Journal of Religion]]'' that ''Religion and Nothingness'' appeals to "a broad theologically or philosophically oriented readership."<ref>[[#Fre93|Fredericks 1993]]. p. 141.</ref>

===Evaluations in books===
Graham Parkes called ''Religion and Nothingness'' Nishitani's masterwork, writing that in it Nishitani achieved a philosophical synthesis that matches the achievements of the philosophers [[Søren Kierkegaard]], [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and [[Martin Heidegger]] in depth of insight.<ref name="Parkes">[[#Par05|Parkes 2005]]. p. 660.</ref>

